# Git Workflow Standards

## Commit Message Format

```
<type>: <description>

<optional body explaining WHY, not WHAT>

Refs: ADR-XXX (if applicable)
```

### Commit Types

| Type | When to Use |
|------|------------|
| `feat` | New feature or functionality |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `refactor` | Code restructuring (no behavior change) |
| `docs` | Documentation changes |
| `test` | Adding or updating tests |
| `chore` | Build, config, dependency updates |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `ci` | CI/CD pipeline changes |
| `security` | Security fix or hardening |

### Examples

```
feat: add project phase transition API

Implements the phase advancement endpoint that moves projects
through the 6-phase lifecycle. Includes validation that all
gate criteria are met before allowing transition.

Refs: ADR-003
```

```
fix: prevent race condition in concurrent project updates

Two users editing the same project simultaneously could overwrite
each other's changes. Added optimistic locking with version column.

Refs: TD-002
```

## Branch Strategy

```
main (production)
  └── develop (integration)
       ├── feature/user-auth      (P0 feature)
       ├── feature/dashboard      (P0 feature)
       ├── fix/login-redirect     (bug fix)
       └── hotfix/security-patch  (production hotfix)
```

- Feature branches from `develop`
- Hotfix branches from `main`
- Merge back to `develop` after hotfix

## Pull Request Workflow

When creating PRs:
1. Analyze full commit history (`git log develop..HEAD`)
2. Use `git diff develop...HEAD` to see all changes
3. Draft comprehensive PR summary with:
   - What changed and why
   - Link to relevant DECISIONS.md ADRs
   - Test coverage report
   - Security impact assessment
4. Include test plan with verification steps

## Pre-Commit Checks

Before every commit, verify:
- [ ] Tests pass (`npm test` / `pytest`)
- [ ] No linting errors
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets (API keys, passwords, tokens)
- [ ] Commit message follows conventional format
- [ ] Changes are scoped to one concern

## Integration with MADF

- Every tech decision logged in DECISIONS.md gets an ADR reference in the commit
- Gate transitions (G1–G6) should be tagged commits
- Hotfixes follow the Reactive Maintenance Agent protocol
- Feature branches map 1:1 to Feature Tracker entries in PROJECT_STATE.md
